article.description:
Karl Malone scored 12 of his 31 points in
the third quarter as the Utah Jazz erased an 11-point deficit and
overcame a flat first half in a 105-63 win over the slumping
Memphis Grizzlies on Wednesday.
article.headline: Mailman scores 31 points as Utah overcomes deficit
article.linkText: Jazz rebound from sluggish first half against Grizzlies
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Karl Malone didn't want to be on the first team to lose to Memphis in two weeks. He didn't want to head into the All-Star break with a three-game losing streak, either.
 
Malone
Malone ensured that neither happened with a 20-point second half, including 12 in the third quarter. The Utah Jazz erased an 11-point deficit and overcame a flat first half in a 105-84 win over the slumping Grizzlies on Wednesday. Malone admitted the All-Star break has been on the minds of the Jazz, who played their sixth game in nine days. "I'm not going to lie to you," Malone said. "I was thinking about it, too, in the beginning, but then you've got to get focused on what you've got to get done." John Stockton had 11 assists and 10 points for the Jazz. Tony Massenburg had 12 rebounds and 11 points, Greg Ostertag scored 10 and pulled down nine rebounds, and Andrei Kirilenko finished with 10 points for Utah. The Jazz played without injured forward Matt Harpring, who has bruised ribs, but that didn't compare with the injury problems the Grizzlies had to deal with. Memphis was without starting point guard Jason Williams and three injured reserves, and wilted in the final two quarters with 12 of the Grizzlies' 20 turnovers in their seventh straight loss. The Jazz were 27-for-42 in the final two quarters while outscoring the injury-depleted Grizzlies 63-35, including 34-14 in the final period. "In the second half we made an effort to get after them on D," Malone said. "You have a tendency when they don't have guys playing to take it for granted because we beat them twice pretty handily." Earl Watson, who replaced Williams, had 16 points in his first NBA start, but only three in the second half. Gordon Giricek led the Grizzlies with 17 points. Lorenzen Wright had 16 points and 13 rebounds and Pau Gasol had 14 points and 11 rebounds. "We ran out of gas, having only seven or eight players," Wright said. "We played our game in the first three quarters, but our legs were not there in the fourth." Memphis went 3-1 against Utah last season, but fell to 0-3 against the Jazz this season. "I don't know what it is. They've got our number," Brown said. "Nobody whacks us like them." The Jazz improved to 3-2 during coach Jerry Sloan's seven-game suspension and entered the All-Star break with a big win that got off to a very sluggish start. The Jazz showed the wear of the last couple of weeks in the first half. Utah committed 10 turnovers and shot just 39 percent, going 7-for-25 from the field in the second quarter. But Malone turned it around in the second half, going 10-for-14 from the floor. After falling behind 55-44 on a 3-pointer by Giricek early in the second, Utah went on a 10-2 run as Malone scored eight straight for the Jazz, starting with a dunk off a full-court pass from Stockton. The Jazz tied it at 65 on a short jumper by Mark Jackson. After the teams traded field goals, Malone finally gave Utah its first lead with a turnaround jumper that put the Jazz up 69-67 with 1:14 left in the third. "He was able to make it work over and over again and that was something to be excited about," Stockton said. The Jazz continued to roll in the fourth by opening with an 11-1 run, including six more points from Malone. With 6:49 to play, Malone blocked Gasol's shot in the Memphis lane and the players remained tangled up after the whistle before breaking apart. Malone, who muttered something to Gasol and shook his head before walking to the Jazz bench to cool off, came back at the other end and hit a 15-footer that put the Jazz up 82-70. Even with the game well in hand, Malone's intensity didn't waver. Stockton hit a layup and was fouled, prompting Malone to point to the Jazz bench from midcourt and shout, "Now that's basketball!" Ostertag attributed Malone's awakening to something the Grizzlies said. "You can't talk trash to one of the best players in the game," Ostertag said. Game notes
The Grizzlies have not won since beating San Antonio 99-93 on Jan. 22. ... Grizzlies reserves Brevin Knight (wrist), Wesley Person (kneecap) and Stromile Swift (hand) did not dress Wednesday. ... Kirilenko will be Utah's only All-Star representative, playing for the second-year team in Saturday's rookie game. ... Malone was called for a flagrant foul on Gasol with 5:12 left in the game. Malone disputed the call, although replays showed his arm came down on Gasol's head. It didn't hurt the Jazz as Gasol missed all three free throws.
